            <ArticleTitle>Structural Insights into Substrate Specificity of Acyltransferases from Salinomycin Polyketide Synthase.</ArticleTitle>
            <ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1021/acs.biochem.9b00305</ELocationID>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText>Salinomycin with antibacterial and anticoccidial activities is a commercial polyether polyketide widely used in animal husbandry as a food additive. Malonyl-CoA (MCoA), methylmalonyl-CoA (MMCoA) and ethylmalonyl-CoA (EMCoA) are used as extension units in its biosynthesis. To understand how the salinomycin modular polyketide synthase (PKS) strictly discriminate between these extension units, the acyltransferase (AT) domains selecting MCoA, MMCoA, and EMCoA respectively were structurally characterized. Molecular dynamics (MD) simulations of the AT structures helped to reveal the key interactions involved in enzyme-substrate recognitions, which enabled the engineering of AT mutants with switched specificity. The catalytic efficiency (kcat/Km) of these AT mutants are comparable with these of the wild-type AT domains. These results set the stage for engineering the AT substrate specificity of modular PKSs.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
